BEGIN:VEVENT
X-SOURCE:UNC Chapel Hill
CATEGORIES:Workshops and Classes
DESCRIPTION:Most people can honestly say they believe it’s important to spe
 nd within their means and to save money for the future. Unfortunately\, goo
 d intentions are often at odds with how our mind works. For example\, many 
 people want to save for the future but have no motivation to because they h
 ave not imagined that future. This course addresses the psychology behind s
 aving money and adopting good financial habits. It will examine recent rese
 arch related to how and why people save vs. spend and identify strategies f
 or participants to change their financial mindset and develop new habits.\n
 \n \n\nWorkshop Objectives\nAt the end of this workshop\, you will be able 
 to:\n• Understand why some people save for the future and other spend for t
 he moment\n• Identify non-productive financial patterns and habits\n• Recog
 nize the mental and behavioral habits of people who save\n• Create a compel
 ling financial future to motivate behavior change\n• Understand how to impr
 ove the capacity to delay gratification while increasing enjoyment\n• Ident
 ify seven simple tools to help change spending habits\n\n \n\nClick on Caro
 lina Talent registration link and select the “Request” button to automatica
 lly enroll.
DTEND:20260417T170000Z
DTSTAMP:20260409T025641Z
DTSTART:20260417T160000Z
LOCATION:
SEQUENCE:0
SUMMARY:The Psychology Behind Saving Money and Other Good Financial Habits
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_51375361584571
URL:https://calendar.unc.edu/event/the-psychology-behind-saving-money-and-o
 ther-good-financial-habits-6916
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
X-SOURCE:UNC Chapel Hill
CATEGORIES:Lectures
DESCRIPTION:On April 17\, African\, African American and diaspora studies p
 rofessor Shakirah Hudani (FFP ’22) will give a lecture titled\, “City Doubl
 ing: Considering Urban Repair from Rwanda.”\n\nShakirah Hudani is an Assist
 ant Professor in the Department of African\, African American and Diaspora 
 Studies (AAAD) at UNC. She is jointly appointed in the Department of City a
 nd Regional Planning (DCRP). Her work concentrates on African urbanism and 
 post-conflict urban change.\n\nThe research for her award-winning book\, Ma
 ster Plans and Minor Acts: Repairing the City in Post-Genocide Rwanda (Univ
 ersity of Chicago Press\, 2024)\, focused on urban change in Rwanda\, with 
 relevance to the Great Lakes region\, and to urban planning processes in Af
 rican cities. She began working in Rwanda in 2002\, examining the Gacaca tr
 ansitional justice process\, and more recently returned to research urbaniz
 ation and contemporary planning. Her new research focuses on peripheral urb
 an change in Nairobi\, Kenya. She has held fellowships from the Institute f
 or the Arts and Humanities at UNC\, the Wenner Gren Foundation\, and is a R
 hodes Scholar (2004).\n\nDrawing on research from her book\, Professor Huda
 ni will discuss urban change in Rwanda in relation to themes on African urb
 anism and post-conflict urbanism. At a time when cities have borne the cost
  of conflict across geographies\, Hudani asks what it means to center repar
 ative strategies in urban space\, focusing on Rwanda and with reference to 
 other conflict-affected sites. Hudani argues that Rwanda’s case shows the n
 eed for attention to local urban pedagogies of place\, so as to integrate t
 raumatic experience rather than erase varied spatial histories and modes of
  remembering.\n\nIntroductions will begin at 12:10. The presentation will b
 e from 12:15 – 12:45 p.m.\, with a Q&A session to follow. Lunch will be ser
 ved.\n\nSee all events in the IAH Fellows Forum series.\n\nRegister for the
  Fellows Forum on Jotform.
DTEND:20260417T173000Z
DTSTAMP:20260409T025641Z
DTSTART:20260417T161000Z
GEO:35.913407;-79.052875
LOCATION:Hyde Hall\, University Room
SEQUENCE:0
